1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,050
All translation is inherently inadequate,
a well-intentioned betrayal.

2
00:00:04,050 --> 00:00:11,662
In the words of the second-century sage
Rabbi Yehudah, One who translates a verse
literally is a liar; one who adds to it is
a blasphemer.

3
00:00:11,662 --> 00:00:23,387
12 Furthermore, the Zohar is notoriously
obscure perhaps the most difficult Jewish
classic to translate. It was composed in
Castile mostly in Aramaic, a language no
longer spoken in medieval Spain.

4
00:00:23,387 --> 00:00:33,212
13 The author(s) concocted a unique blend
of Aramaic out of traditional sources,
especially the Babylonian Talmud and
Targum Onqelos (an Aramaic translation of
the Torah).

5
00:00:33,212 --> 00:00:43,949
This unparalleled neo-Aramaic is peppered
with enigmatic expressions, puns,
outlandish constructions, puzzling
neologisms, solecisms, and traces of
medieval Hebrew and Castilian.

6
00:00:43,949 --> 00:00:52,711
The Zohar s prose is poetic, overflowing
with multiple connotations, composed in
such a way that you often cannot pin down
the precise meaning of a phrase.

7
00:00:52,711 --> 00:00:59,398
The language befits the subject matter,
which is mysterious, elusive, and
ineffable; words can merely suggest and
hint.

8
00:00:59,398 --> 00:01:04,823
An unfathomable process may be stated,
then immediately denied: It split and did
not split its aura.

9
00:01:04,823 --> 00:01:14,985
14 Occasionally we encounter oxymorons,
such as new-ancient words, alluding to the
dual nature of the Zohar s secrets,
recently composed yet ascribed to ancient
sources.

10
00:01:14,985 --> 00:01:25,260
15 The first impulse of divine emanation
is described as (botsina de-qardinuta), a
spark of impenetrable darkness, 16 so
intensely bright that it cannot be seen.

11
00:01:25,260 --> 00:01:31,610
Through the centuries, the potency of the
Zohar s language has mesmerized even those
who could not plumb its secrets.

12
00:01:31,610 --> 00:01:37,897
While kabbalists delved deeply, the
uninitiated chanted the lyrical Aramaic,
often unaware of its literal meaning.

13
00:01:37,897 --> 00:01:43,709
In the words of an eighteenth-century
mystic, Even if one does not understand,
the language is suited to the soul.

14
00:01:43,709 --> 00:01:51,546
17 No doubt it is risky to translate the
Zohar, but it would be worse to leave
these gems of wisdom buried in their
ancient Aramaic vault.

15
00:01:51,546 --> 00:01:55,608
So I have plunged in, seeking to transmit
some of the Zohar s magic.

16
00:01:55,608 --> 00:02:05,620
The previous English translation (composed
in the 1930s by Harry Sperling, Maurice
Simon, and Paul Levertoff) reads smoothly
but often misunderstands the text.

17
00:02:05,620 --> 00:02:16,770
18 Its genteel prose is more a paraphrase
than an accurate translation avoiding
unfamiliar terms, censoring erotic
material, skipping difficult passages and
even entire sections.

18
00:02:16,770 --> 00:02:23,782
The English flows too fluently compared to
the original, subduing the unruly Aramaic,
failing to render its untamed vibrancy.

19
00:02:23,782 --> 00:02:35,307
Moreover, since the translation is
unaccompanied by a commentary, the
symbolism remains impenetrable. Despite
its shortcomings, I have learned much from
consulting this translation, along with
others.

20
00:02:35,307 --> 00:02:47,694
19 But my approach is significantly
different. Though I wish to make the Zohar
accessible, I also want to convey its
strangeness, potency, and rich ambiguity.
Here the commentary is essential.

21
00:02:47,694 --> 00:02:54,131
When the translation cannot adequately
express a multifaceted phrase, I unfold
the range of meaning in the commentary.

22
00:02:54,131 --> 00:03:02,668
When the translation is as cryptic as the
original Aramaic, the commentary rescues
the stranded reader. My style of
translation is literal yet poetic.

23
00:03:02,668 --> 00:03:12,480
I am convinced that a literal rendering of
the Zohar is not only the most accurate
but also the most colorful and zestful the
best way to transmit the lyrical energy of
the Aramaic.

24
00:03:12,480 --> 00:03:19,580
Still, at times, the multivalent language
invites a certain freedom of expression.
Let me cite two related examples.

25
00:03:19,580 --> 00:03:29,767
In Zohar 1: 83a, Rabbi Shim on describes
the nighttime journey of the soul, soaring
skyward from her sleeping body: Flying,
she encounters those (qumrin tehirin) of
defilement.

26
00:03:29,767 --> 00:03:36,042
What does this bizarre term mean? The
Sperling-Simon translation renders it as
certain bright but unclean essences.

27
00:03:36,042 --> 00:03:41,754
20 The English translation of Tishby s
Wisdom of the Zohar reads: the deceiving
lights of uncleanness

28
00:03:41,754 --> 00:03:51,691
21 while Tishby s original Hebrew
translation reads a bit differently:
(qimmurei negohot) roughly: vaulted
splendors though in his note he
acknowledges that the meaning is doubtful.

29
00:03:51,691 --> 00:03:58,766
22 I render the sentence as follows:
Flying, she encounters those hooded,
hunchbacked, dazzling demons of
defilement.

30
00:03:58,766 --> 00:04:04,628
The accompanying commentary explains that
these are malevolent forces who block the
ascent of an unworthy soul.

31
00:04:04,628 --> 00:04:16,640
Qumrin derives via rabbinic usage from the
Greek qamara, arched cover, while tehirin
is a cognate of the Aramaic tihara,
meaning brightness, noon. One class of
demons is named tiharei, noonday demons.

32
00:04:16,640 --> 00:04:21,490
The virtuous soul who evades these demons
reaches heaven and receives a divine
message.

33
00:04:21,490 --> 00:04:30,190
According to another Zoharic passage (1:
130a), while descending back to her
sleeping earthbound body, the soul is
assailed by ( avilei teriqin).

34
00:04:30,190 --> 00:04:40,777
The Sperling-Simon translation renders
this phrase as malignant bands. 23 The
English translation of Tishby s Wisdom of
the Zohar reads: ill-intentioned
destructive powers.

35
00:04:40,777 --> 00:04:51,514
24 I render it as ravaging bands of
truculent stingers. The commentary
explains that avilei derives from either
evel, band, group, or the verb vl, to
injure, destroy.

36
00:04:51,514 --> 00:05:00,289
Teriqin derives from the root trq, to
sting, bite. Although the Zohar s basic
vocabulary is limited, its roots generate
a rich variety of meanings.

37
00:05:00,289 --> 00:05:09,501
For example, the root (tqn) spans the
following range: establish, institute,
mend, restore, correct, perfect, prepare,
arrange, array, adorn.

38
00:05:09,501 --> 00:05:18,826
The root (slq) can mean: rise, raise,
culminate, attain, surpass, depart,
disappear, die, remove, postpone, reserve,
emit (fragrance).

39
00:05:18,826 --> 00:05:29,038
In normal Aramaic and Hebrew the specific
verbal conjugation determines which
meaning of the root applies but the Zohar
ignores or flouts rules of grammar
confusing the conjugations

40
00:05:29,038 --> 00:05:32,988
playing with multiple meanings often
leaving the reader stumped and wondering.

41
00:05:32,988 --> 00:05:39,813
Mysticism strives to penetrate a realm
beyond distinctions but this mystical
masterpiece demands constant decision
making

42
00:05:39,813 --> 00:05:50,338
challenging the reader or translator to
navigate between conflicting meanings and
determine the appropriate one or sometimes
to discover how differing meanings pertain
simultaneously.

43
00:05:50,338 --> 00:05:58,013
The frequent dilemmas of interpretation
suggest that in exploring the Zohar,
linguistic search and spiritual search go
hand in hand.

44
00:05:58,013 --> 00:06:05,050
Especially puzzling, though charming, are
the neologisms strewn throughout the
Zohar, intended to bewilder and astound
the reader.

45
00:06:05,050 --> 00:06:17,050
25 Some derive from rare Talmudic terms
which the author refashions by
intentionally misspelling or by inverting
letters some derive from Greek Latin or
Castilian some appear to be pure
inventions.

46
00:06:17,050 --> 00:06:27,337
These nonce words often contain the
letters (tet), (samekh), (pe), (qof), and
(resh) in various combinations: (quspita),
(qatpira), (qirta), (qesira), (qustera),
(tufsera).

47
00:06:27,337 --> 00:06:38,287
Qustera derives from the Latin word
castrum (plural, castra), fortress,
castle. Qatpira and its variations mean
several things, including knot (based on
Aramaic [qitra]) and waterskin.

48
00:06:38,287 --> 00:06:48,674
26 One newly coined noun, (tiqla), is
particularly versatile. In various
contexts it can mean scale, hollow of the
hand, fist, potter s wheel, and water
clock.

49
00:06:48,674 --> 00:06:56,461
This last sense refers to a device
described in ancient and medieval
scientific literature which in the Zohar
functions as an alarm clock

50
00:06:56,461 --> 00:07:06,748
calibrated to wake kabbalists precisely at
midnight for the ritual study of Torah. 27
A similar device was employed in Christian
monasteries to rouse monks for their
vigils.

51
00:07:06,748 --> 00:07:09,498
How appropriate to invent a word for an
invention!

52
00:07:09,498 --> 00:07:20,485
Often by pondering the context comparing
Zoharic and rabbinic parallels and
scouring sundry dictionaries and lexicons
one can decipher or at least conjecture
the meaning of these weird terms

53
00:07:20,485 --> 00:07:30,497
but some remain as perplexing as
originally intended. 28 In translating
biblical citations, I have consulted
various translations but generally
composed my own.

54
00:07:30,497 --> 00:07:37,547
29 Sometimes, in quoting a verse, the
Zohar intends a meaning different from
that conveyed by any known translation.

55
00:07:37,547 --> 00:07:44,184
In such cases I usually translate the
verse as the Zohar understands it and then
explain the difference in the commentary.

56
00:07:44,184 --> 00:07:49,546
The main purpose of the commentary is to
clarify the dense symbolism and unique
terminology.

57
00:07:49,546 --> 00:07:59,096
Here I seek to elicit the meaning of the
text, drawing it forth from the Zohar s
own language without being heavy-handed
without ruining the subtlety and ambiguity
of the original.

58
00:07:59,096 --> 00:08:07,408
Remember that the Zohar was not intended
to be easily understood but rather to be
deciphered. I want to allow and compel the
reader to wrestle with the text.

59
00:08:07,408 --> 00:08:16,945
Over the centuries, the tendency has grown
to overinterpret, with commentators often
insisting on assigning sefirotic
significance to nearly every image and
metaphor.

60
00:08:16,945 --> 00:08:23,195
I have resisted this tendency, while still
identifying sefirotic correspondences when
they are called for.

61
00:08:23,195 --> 00:08:29,082
Often a phrase or passage implies more
than one meaning; the reader is encouraged
to ponder various possibilities.

62
00:08:29,082 --> 00:08:38,494
To clarify the context, I cite sources and
parallels from the Bible, rabbinic
literature, and the Zohar itself, with
occasional references to secondary
literature.

63
00:08:38,494 --> 00:08:46,719
The aim is not to overwhelm the reader by
citing everything conceivable, but rather
to provide what is needed to make sense of
this enigmatic work of art.

64
00:08:46,719 --> 00:08:58,256
30 In composing the commentary I have
drawn on numerous traditional and modern
Zohar commentaries especially those of
Moses Cordovero Shim on Lavi ayyim Vital
Abraham Galante Shalom Buzaglo

65
00:08:58,256 --> 00:09:00,918
Yehudah Ashlag Charles Mopsik and Daniel
Frisch.

66
00:09:00,918 --> 00:09:11,843
31 Other valuable resources include the
annotations of Reuven Margaliot (Nitsotsei
Zohar) in his edition of the Zohar Isaiah
Tishby s monumental Mishnat ha-Zohar (The
Wisdom of the Zohar)

67
00:09:11,843 --> 00:09:19,568
Gershom Scholem s Annotated Zohar and
Yehuda Liebes s eye-opening Peraqim
be-Millon Sefer ha-Zohar (Sections of the
Zohar Lexicon).

68
00:09:19,568 --> 00:09:29,755
A glossary, bibliography, and an index of
biblical and rabbinic citations are
appended to each volume. A diagram of the
ten sefirot appears on page xi of this
volume.

69
00:09:29,755 --> 00:09:36,642
The standard Aramaic pagination of the
Zohar is indicated in the running head on
each page (e. g. , 1: 34b).

70
00:09:36,642 --> 00:09:45,292
How to Read the Zohar There is no single
right way to read and proceed through the
Zohar, but I can point out certain
features and suggest several guidelines.

71
00:09:45,292 --> 00:09:48,654
First of all, the Zohar is dynamic full of
surprises.

72
00:09:48,654 --> 00:09:58,441
Typically we find that Rabbi iyya and
Rabbi Yose were walking on the way
wandering through the hills of Galilee
sharing secrets of Torah but also moving
from one dimension to another

73
00:09:58,441 --> 00:10:03,641
accompanied by Shekhinah the Divine
Presence Herself. Who knows whom they will
encounter on the road?

74
00:10:03,641 --> 00:10:14,616
A child amazes them with wisdom, a beggar
enriches them with precious teachings, a
cantankerous old donkey-driver turns out
to be a sage in disguise. You are about to
enter an enchanted realm.

75
00:10:14,616 --> 00:10:21,491
Still, although the Zohar sometimes reads
like a mystical novel, remember that this
is fundamentally a biblical commentary.

76
00:10:21,491 --> 00:10:28,991
It s helpful to have a Bible at hand to
check the original context, to see how a
particular verse becomes a springboard for
the imagination.

77
00:10:28,991 --> 00:10:38,953
Every few pages we read: Rabbi iyya opened
Rabbi Yose opened signifying that he is
opening not only his exposition but also
the verse: disclosing new layers of
meaning

78
00:10:38,953 --> 00:10:49,815
expanding the range of interpretation. The
reader of the Zohar should be open, too
open to new ways of thinking and
imagining. As the avrayya (Companions)
continually exclaim, Come and see!

79
00:10:49,815 --> 00:10:58,840
The Zohar is firmly rooted in tradition
but thrives on discovery. This verse has
been discussed, but come and see! This
verse has been established, but come and
see!

80
00:10:58,840 --> 00:11:07,927
32 Innovations of Torah are required here!
33 Innovation emerges through scrutinizing
the biblical text, so questioning becomes
a supreme value.

81
00:11:07,927 --> 00:11:14,939
After Rabbi izkiyah asks Rabbi Abba a
challenging question, we are told that
Rabbi Abba came and kissed him. 34 Why?

82
00:11:14,939 --> 00:11:21,739
Because, as one commentator notes here,
The question is half the answer; without a
question, there is no reason for an
answer.

83
00:11:21,739 --> 00:11:29,951
35 Even when the meaning of a verse is
perfectly clear, the Zohar may question
its structure, sometimes probing so deeply
that the reader is stunned.

84
00:11:29,951 --> 00:11:39,838
To take an extreme example, come and see
how Rabbi El azar deals with the
concluding verse in the story of the
Garden of Eden, which could hardly be more
explicit: He drove out Adam.

85
00:11:39,838 --> 00:11:44,888
36 We do not know who divorced whom: if
the blessed Holy One divorced Adam, or
not.

86
00:11:44,888 --> 00:11:55,125
37 As the rabbi demonstrates by exegetical
artifice the mystical meaning is the
shocking alternative lurking within that
bland phrase or not : Adam drove out
divorced Shekhinah

87
00:11:55,125 --> 00:12:01,612
splitting Her from Her divine partner Tif
eret and from himself. Once, as Adam,
humanity was wedded to God.

88
00:12:01,612 --> 00:12:07,162
The original sin lies in losing intimacy
with the divine, thereby constricting
unbounded awareness.

89
00:12:07,162 --> 00:12:13,874
This loss follows inevitably from tasting
the fruit of discursive knowledge; it is
the price we pay for maturity and culture.

90
00:12:13,874 --> 00:12:18,874
The spiritual challenge is to search for
that lost treasure without renouncing the
self or the world.

91
00:12:18,874 --> 00:12:24,911
As you read, see how the avrayya coax new
meaning out of a biblical verse, phrase,
word or even letter.

92
00:12:24,911 --> 00:12:32,773
Often they rely on standard rabbinic
techniques of interpretation such as
verbal analogy: Here is written:
[such-and-such a biblical expression]

93
00:12:32,773 --> 00:12:39,010
and there is written: [an identical (or
nearly identical) expression] implying a
close link between the two expressions.

94
00:12:39,010 --> 00:12:48,960
The hermeneutical leap may be long, far
from the literal meaning, but sometimes a
verse is read hyperliterally, ignoring
idiomatic usage in favor of a radically
spiritual sense.

95
00:12:48,960 --> 00:12:53,185
For example, when God commands Abraham,
(Lekh lekha), Go forth, ...

96
00:12:53,185 --> 00:13:01,760
to the land that I will show you (Genesis
12: 1), Rabbi El azar insists on reading
the words more literally than they were
intended: Lekh lekha, Go to yourself!

97
00:13:01,760 --> 00:13:11,897
38 Search deep within to discover your
true self. Another startling illustration
is the Zohar s reading of the opening
words of the Torah, traditionally
rendered: In the beginning God created.

98
00:13:11,897 --> 00:13:20,909
Everyone assumes the verse describes the
creation of the world, but for the Zohar
it alludes to a more primal beginning: the
emanation of the sefirot from Ein Sof (
Infinity ).

99
00:13:20,909 --> 00:13:23,484
How is this allusion discovered, or
invented?

100
00:13:23,484 --> 00:13:33,484
By insisting on reading the Hebrew words
in their precise order: (Bereshit bara
Elohim) construed now as With beginning It
created Elohim that is by means of okhmah
(the sefirah of Wisdom

101
00:13:33,484 --> 00:13:44,309
known as beginning) It (ineffable Ein Sof)
emanated Binah (the sefirah of
Understanding known by the divine name
Elohim). 39 God, it turns out, is the
object of the verse, not the subject!

102
00:13:44,309 --> 00:13:49,921
The ultimate divine reality, Ein Sof,
transcends and explodes our comfortable
conception of God.

103
00:13:49,921 --> 00:14:00,783
The Zohar dares us to confront this
reality, as it transforms the familiar
story of Creation into divine biography.
So, as you undertake this adventure,
expect to be surprised stay alert.

104
00:14:00,783 --> 00:14:09,920
The Zohar s teachings are profound and
intense; one who hopes to enter and emerge
in peace should be careful, persevering,
simultaneously receptive and active.

105
00:14:09,920 --> 00:14:19,670
The message is not served to you on a
platter; you must engage the text and join
the search for meaning. Follow the words
to what lies beyond and within; open the
gates of imagination.

106
00:14:19,670 --> 00:14:28,457
Above all, don t reduce everything you
encounter in these pages to something you
already know. Beware of trying to find the
essence of a particular teaching.

107
00:14:28,457 --> 00:14:39,169
Although usually essence is the goal of
mystical search, here essence is
inadequate unless it stimulates you to
explore ever deeper layers, to question
your assumptions about tradition, God, and
self.

108
00:14:39,169 --> 00:14:49,681
In the words of a Zoharic parable: There
was a man who lived in the mountains. He
knew nothing about those who lived in the
city. He sowed wheat and ate the kernels
raw. One day he entered the city.

109
00:14:49,681 --> 00:14:59,931
They offered him good bread. The man
asked, What s this for? They replied, It s
bread, to eat! He ate, and it tasted very
good. He asked, What s it made of? They
answered, Wheat.

110
00:14:59,931 --> 00:15:09,993
Later they offered him thick loaves
kneaded with oil. He tasted them, and
asked, And what are these made of? They
answered, Wheat. Later they offered him
royal pastry kneaded with honey and oil.

111
00:15:09,993 --> 00:15:18,168
He asked, And what are these made of? They
answered, Wheat. He said, Surely I am the
master of all of these, since I eat the
essence of all of these: wheat!

112
00:15:18,168 --> 00:15:22,443
Because of that view, he knew nothing of
the delights of the world, which were lost
on him.

113
00:15:22,443 --> 00:15:29,955
So it is with one who grasps the principle
but is unaware of all those delectable
delights deriving, diverging from that
principle.

114
00:15:29,955 --> 00:15:36,342
40 Acknowledgments the people who have
helped me begin to plumb the Zohar would
burst TO THANK ALL this book s binding.

115
00:15:36,342 --> 00:15:41,592
So here I will briefly trace my path and
acknowledge some of those who have helped
me along the way.

116
00:15:41,592 --> 00:15:50,579
My father, of blessed memory, Rabbi
Hershel Jonah Matt, taught me that God is
real, and that by studying Torah you can
experience Shekhinah, the Divine Presence.

117
00:15:50,579 --> 00:16:00,479
(I have sketched his life and assembled
his writings in Walking Humbly with God. )
My mother, Gustine, has always been a
fountain of love and a source of strength;
I am grateful for her deep wisdom.

118
00:16:00,479 --> 00:16:07,566
I first ventured into Sefer ha-Zohar in
1970 during my junior year abroad at
Hebrew University in Jerusalem.

119
00:16:07,566 --> 00:16:14,241
The thick volumes were simultaneously
forbidding and alluring; deciphering the
Aramaic text was a puzzle, a challenge, a
quest.

120
00:16:14,241 --> 00:16:19,253
Soon I fell in love with the Zohar,
captivated by its lush imagery and poetic
magic.

121
00:16:19,253 --> 00:16:29,128
My teachers that year in Kabbalah included
Joseph Dan, Efraim Gottlieb, and Rivka
Schatz-Uffenheimer and a kabbalist, Rav
Toledano. I thank them all for guiding me
into the orchard.

122
00:16:29,128 --> 00:16:40,490
From Jerusalem I returned to Brandeis
University where I completed my
undergraduate degree and then after some
European travel plunged into graduate
study in Jewish mysticism with Alexander
Altmann

123
00:16:40,490 --> 00:16:43,302
a superb Wissenschaft scholar and a gem of
a man.

124
00:16:43,302 --> 00:16:54,539
He directed my doctoral dissertation which
consisted of a critical edition of The
Book of Mirrors a previously unpublished
fourteenth-century Hebrew commentary on
the Torah by David ben Judah he- asid.

125
00:16:54,539 --> 00:17:01,201
I chose to edit this text because it
included the first extended translations
of the Zohar, from Aramaic to Hebrew.

126
00:17:01,201 --> 00:17:08,638
I was encouraged to undertake this project
by Gershom Scholem, while serving as his
teaching assistant in the fall of 1975.

127
00:17:08,638 --> 00:17:17,713
After I completed my dissertation my
friend Arthur Green invited me to compose
an annotated translation of selections
from the Zohar for the Paulist Press

128
00:17:17,713 --> 00:17:28,063
as one volume in their Classics of Western
Spirituality. Years earlier, Art had
initiated me into the mystical thought of
Hasidism, which stimulated me to uncover
its roots in the Zohar.

129
00:17:28,063 --> 00:17:35,025
I am grateful for his insight and guidance
over the years, and for demonstrating how
to combine scholarship and spirituality.

130
00:17:35,025 --> 00:17:46,412
For two decades, I taught Jewish mysticism
in Berkeley at the Graduate Theological
Union (GTU), a school where Jews,
Christians, and Buddhists study side by
side, stimulating one another.

131
00:17:46,412 --> 00:17:55,462
I learned much there from my colleagues
and students; I want to thank, in
particular, David Winston and David Biale
for their friendship and for the depth of
their learning.

132
00:17:55,462 --> 00:18:06,387
I had been at the GTU for many years
already when, one afternoon in September
1995, Art Green called me on the phone and
told me about a woman from Chicago named
Margot Pritzker.

133
00:18:06,387 --> 00:18:13,337
She had been studying the Zohar with Rabbi
Yehiel Poupko, but the dated English
translation they were reading had proved
inadequate.

134
00:18:13,337 --> 00:18:23,949
Margot had decided to commission a new
translation, said Art, and she was
inviting me to undertake the task! I was
astounded, and told my friend that I
needed a few days to consider this.

135
00:18:23,949 --> 00:18:30,236
The days turned into weeks, which turned
into months, as I kept wrestling with the
thrilling, terrifying offer.

136
00:18:30,236 --> 00:18:41,386
I decided to translate a short section of
the Zohar to see how it felt, but I poured
myself into the experiment so intensely,
day after day, that I was left drained,
exhausted, discouraged.

137
00:18:41,386 --> 00:18:43,748
How could I keep this up for years and
years?

138
00:18:43,748 --> 00:18:52,910
I reluctantly resolved to decline the
offer, but Art convinced me to at least
meet this woman and her rabbi; so the
following May, the four of us gathered at
the O Hare Hyatt.

139
00:18:52,910 --> 00:19:01,047
I expressed my hesitation to them, and
told Margot that the project could take
twelve to fifteen years to which she
responded, You re not scaring me!

140
00:19:01,047 --> 00:19:06,909
I was won over by her genuine desire to
penetrate the Zohar and make it accessible
to English readers.

141
00:19:06,909 --> 00:19:18,509
A year or so later, over Independence Day
weekend 1997, the Zohar project formally
began with a two-day conference outside
Chicago attended by the leading academic
scholars of Kabbalah.

142
00:19:18,509 --> 00:19:28,696
They were invited not just to participate
in this conference but to constitute the
Academic Committee for the Translation of
the Zohar, which was intended to guide and
support this translation.

143
00:19:28,696 --> 00:19:36,946
(The members of the committee are listed
at the front of this volume. ) Over the
past six years, I have benefited immensely
from their feedback and encouragement.

144
00:19:36,946 --> 00:19:48,596
I thank all of them, especially Moshe
Idel, Yehuda Liebes, Ronit Meroz, and
Elliot Wolfson. Time and again, Yehuda
generously shared insights drawn from his
vast, intimate knowledge of the Zohar.

145
00:19:48,596 --> 00:19:55,758
I smile, recalling the many times we
wrestled over the mystifying Aramaic,
deepening our understanding of the text
and our friendship.

146
00:19:55,758 --> 00:20:08,145
I spent the second year of the project
(1998 99) at the Institute for Advanced
Studies at the Hebrew University of
Jerusalem on a program entitled Studying
the Zohar, directed by Yehuda Liebes.

147
00:20:08,145 --> 00:20:16,982
Here seven fellows and seven other
visiting scholars (all fourteen of us,
members of the Academic Committee) engaged
in research on various aspects of the
text.

148
00:20:16,982 --> 00:20:23,507
Our weekly seminars were devoted to a
close reading of Zohar passages often
those that I was currently translating.

149
00:20:23,507 --> 00:20:28,932
Here I presented a draft of my translation
and benefited from the responses of my
colleagues.

150
00:20:28,932 --> 00:20:35,419
I am grateful to all of them, as well as
to the staff of the Institute, who
provided an ideal setting for our
research.

151
00:20:35,419 --> 00:20:43,344
When the yearlong program ended in June
1999, the institute graciously allowed me
to retain an office for the following year
as well.

152
00:20:43,344 --> 00:20:48,531
In the summer of 2000, it was finally time
to leave the tranquil environment of the
institute.

153
00:20:48,531 --> 00:20:54,256
Fortunately Rabbi David Hartman provided
me with an office at the Shalom Hartman
Institute across town

154
00:20:54,256 --> 00:21:00,993
where I spent the following two years
(2000 2002) in an atmosphere
simultaneously peaceful and stimulating.

155
00:21:00,993 --> 00:21:10,355
David s enthusiasm for Torah energizes
everyone around him, and I thank him for
his support and encouragement, and for his
healthy skepticism of mystical excess.

156
00:21:10,355 --> 00:21:20,630
I was enriched by my contact with many of
the fellows at the Hartman Institute
especially Donniel Hartman (co-director)
Daniel Abrams Moshe Halbertal Moshe Idel
Israel Knohl Levi Lauer

157
00:21:20,630 --> 00:21:28,430
Menachem Lorberbaum Yair Lorberbaum Israel
Ta-Shma and Shlomo Naeh. Shlomo was always
generous in sharing with me his immense
linguistic knowledge.

158
00:21:28,430 --> 00:21:39,780
As described in the Translator s
Introduction I have based my English
rendering on a critical text of the Zohar
which I have constructed by drawing on
variant readings from a wide range of
manuscripts.

159
00:21:39,780 --> 00:21:44,830
I could not have accomplished this task
without my indefatigable research
assistant Barry Mark

160
00:21:44,830 --> 00:21:55,042
who spent more than five years
painstakingly preparing lists of these
variants for the first two volumes of the
translation. I thank him immensely for his
years of devotion to this task.

161
00:21:55,042 --> 00:22:02,354
Recently, Merav Carmeli has followed in
his footsteps, proving herself a worthy
successor, and I am indebted to her as
well.

162
00:22:02,354 --> 00:22:10,154
Arthur Green has carefully read large
portions of this translation and offered
criticism and suggestions, for which I am
truly grateful.

163
00:22:10,154 --> 00:22:16,241
As co-chair of the Academic Committee for
the Translation of the Zohar, he has
helped guide the project from its birth.

164
00:22:16,241 --> 00:22:27,428
Numerous libraries offered valuable
resources especially the Gershom Scholem
